text: Finally we have been waiting for this since they first announced it. Charlie Hunnam plays the legendary warrior king known for pulling the sword from the stone. We have Petyr Baelish and Roose Bolton in this film too. Eric Bana plays Uther Pendragon(Arthur's dad) while Jude Law plays evil uncle Vortigern(who was just in Once Upon a Time as Vortigan). This film comes out the same day as Power Rangers and I know both movies will do amazing at the box office because we have both Jude Law and Elizabeth Banks playing fantastic magical badass villains Vortigern and Rita Repulsa. What's the same is it's the battle of the dragons of red and white because it's Arthur(the red) vs Vortigern(the white) in place of his father Uther Pendragon and uncle Ambrosius Aurelianus who both battled Vortigern in the original Arthurian Legends.

text: *All these comments show how uneducated some people are.* *1)* King Arthur was not alive during medieval times. He was alive during the Roman Empire, near its ruin but not quite into the Medieval Ages when there became an immense power struggle. He was most likely a Roman Centurion, himself.  *2)* The Roman Empire controlled all of North Africa. It is ignorant to assume no blacks would be in Europe, especially given that this was well before white racism. Racism started in the Americas in circa 1600, when a guy sold the first (in the Americas, I mean) black slaves to colonists.  *3)* There was a Knight of the Round Table that was African. I thought his name was Sir Morian, but the comments spell it Sir Morien so I guess I forgot the spelling. He was introduced into the Arthurian legends sometime before the United States was a country. It is not a work of SJWs.  *4)* Stop bitching about historical accuracy when you don't even _know_ the term.

text: Scrolling down the comments certain people seem to be wondering how there can be a Black Character in an ancient story based in Europe England. If you guys did your research you would know Black people have had contact with Europe for a very long time even going back to the BC era. for example the Greeks called Black Africans from the Kingdom of Kush aka Nubia Aethiopians which meant Burnt Face people. Even in Greek Mythology Andromida is Aethiopian Princess. Plus the Trojian war had one of the only warriors in the story to fight Achilles on Equal grounds King Memnon again Aethiopian king who brought his army in the story to support Troy. Hannibal Barca's army had a significant amount of Blacks and Berbers in it, evidence are the skulls found on battle fields and in Carthage and the coins made in his honor in Europe with a Black head on it.  Later on in Europe in early Medieval times they called Blacks and other peoples such has Arabs and caucasian Berbers entering Europe from Morocco Moors. The from these groups of the Blacks were sometimes known has BlackaMoors, there are house symbols which had black faces and heads in Europe has well has paintings of Rich Black people and knights living amongst Europeans.

text: Africans in Dark Ages Britain? Really?  And for those of you who say "the Moors" - the Arthur legends were Dark Ages, after Rome left the British Isles, and the land was without a ruler. So we are talking closer to 500 AD, while Mohammed didn't even appear until a hundred years later. The Moors didn't invade Spain until 711, and never invaded England. Plus the actor in the trailer is a sub-saharan African, not northern African or Arab anyway.   I know the reason why - both the US and UK are multiracial societies, and there's a push to make history multicultural too, so that everyone feels included. Yes, this is a fairy tale, but a EUROPEAN fairy tale. I would also object to white actors being used in Chinese or African fairy tales as well.

I studied a lot about Middle Ages and took a bunch of time to find out there were actually black people on Europe this times.  The matter is black people are not original from  Europe, but they arrived there at some point, known as the Moorish and they were a minority, what gives some logic on thinking there were no black guys there.  Anyway, I still hate the way they are portrayed in blockbusters, they have to turn a white supporting character in black (Nick Fury, Heimdall) or they are there just because they need to include diversity in the film (Finn on SW). text: I love Guy Ritchie and his directive Style and I also love and adore the Legend of King Arthur. So I should be happy right? I wonder why I am still worried...probably because in the past they messed up the Legend of King Arthur so many times. Besides the Mists of Avalon their is almost no good interpretation, and that one only works because of the book, and is still not as good as the book. Not at all. So I really don't how to feel about this. Especially because I love Guy Ritchie for his fun and entertaining movies. But the Legend of King Arthur is not just fun and entertaining...its so much more. It has such a deep story to it. The Movie seems to part from the storyline prett heavily. So I am scared. I am excited for a fun Guy Ritchie Movie but I don't think that Arthur was the right topic to choose.

text: For those hating this film for its "historical inaccuracy", read some books before watching films because you sound plain stupid. Arthur wasn't even a historical figure, he was a character of many versions of French medieval literature, the most famous one being Chretien de Troyes' arthurian romances. There could have been black people, Chinese people at that time, since your mind conceives that black people didn't have a life before made slaves by the American, but they were trading all around the world, today's Spain was full of Maori people and even centuries after, Shakespeare's Othello was black or arab, so what the fuck are you talking about?   The huge elephant scenes were also present in Lord of the Rings, 300 and other films and no one bitched about it then, so why hate this film so much? If you watch all the films made after Shakespeare's plays, even that abomination called Titus, you would see that not in all films they are wearing tights and keep to the tone and script, so hating this film for its inaccuracies about nothing, because you haven't even read the original writings on Arthur is just plain stupid.  I found it lovely, the music is amazing and Charlie Hunnam deserves a thousand rounds of applause for his performance in this lead role. In my opinion, this is the most misjudged film in history.

text: Watch this movie despite everything. Period. You'll not be disappointed or regret watching this, hell the only thing you'll regret is that you didn't watch this in the theatres. The critics have judged this wrong. . The casting is great, Jude Law and Eric Bana(though short-lived in his role as Uther) outshone in their respective roles. The Music by Daniel Pemberton in this movie is distinctive and addictive. Sam Lee's interpretation of Wild Wild Berry is eargasm in Daniel Pemberton's The Devil and The Huntsman. Guy's Reimagination of the age-old tale with creative storytelling and distinctive acts of screenplay. If not for anything, you can still watch this movie for its visual treats. Guy Ritchie's Direction was spot on as always. . A girl asked me out to this movie which I declined, I got what I deserved for trusting critics judgement more than Guy Ritchie's Direction, a lost chance to watch this in theatres.
